00:35:58.369 --> 00:36:04.170
So that said, it's not very difficult to port
and open GLES game that's written in C to

00:36:04.170 --> 00:36:05.170
Android.

00:36:05.170 --> 00:36:07.420
There are some issues.

00:36:07.420 --> 00:36:11.820
A lot of people think that since Android is
Linux, it should be very easy to port any

00:36:11.820 --> 00:36:13.300
piece of Linux software.

00:36:13.300 --> 00:36:15.390
And that's not entirely true.

00:36:15.390 --> 00:36:21.340
Because Android like all other Linux systems
is build out of a lot of different components.

00:36:21.340 --> 00:36:24.640
And there are some things you can pick and
choose in terms of the libraries, internal

00:36:24.640 --> 00:36:25.640
chains.

00:36:25.640 --> 00:36:28.710
We have a specific C runtime that we use called
bionic.

00:36:28.710 --> 00:36:32.220
That a lot of other people don't use.

00:36:32.220 --> 00:36:35.000
And all of this adds up to more hassle.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:41.650
Now, normally for a Linux system this isn't
a hassle because you use something like apt

00:36:41.650 --> 00:36:46.660
or you know, macports or one of these things
that compiles everything and runs through

00:36:46.660 --> 00:36:47.770
a bunch of compatibility scripts.

00:36:47.770 --> 00:36:51.730
And if you've ever used a port system, you
know that there's like a million different

00:36:51.730 --> 00:36:54.790
tasks to figure out where your C runtime lives.

00:36:54.790 --> 00:36:57.060
And where your pilot lives and all these other
things.

00:36:57.060 --> 00:36:58.340
Android of course doesn't do that.

00:36:58.340 --> 00:37:00.640
We distribute binaries to the phone.

00:37:00.640 --> 00:37:02.359
Or to the device.

00:37:02.359 --> 00:37:10.780
So you are not able to count on all of the
things that your desktop Linux system has.

00:37:10.780 --> 00:37:15.820
Or even all of the things that are in the
Android open source project right now.

00:37:15.820 --> 00:37:18.310
What we do instead is we release something
called the NDK.

00:37:18.310 --> 00:37:21.380
The native development kit.

00:37:21.380 --> 00:37:22.840
There's a lot of things in the NDK.

00:37:22.840 --> 00:37:28.150
But the real core of it, the irreplaceable
piece of it is a set of headers that form

00:37:28.150 --> 00:37:31.940
a contract that Google has decided we will
always fulfill.

00:37:31.940 --> 00:37:36.010
&gt;&gt;Dan g: Yeah, it has an NADI, an application
binary interface.

00:37:36.010 --> 00:37:41.089
And the key thing about that is that for your
open GL calls, those open GL calls will be

00:37:41.089 --> 00:37:43.480
essentially identical because open GL is a
standard.

00:37:43.480 --> 00:37:46.550
It actually provides a contracted ABI itself.

00:37:46.550 --> 00:37:47.920
And we're adhering to that contract.

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:53.720
So from an open GL perspective all the open
GL code should port over incredibly easily.

00:37:53.720 --> 00:37:58.110
Obviously, if you're taking advantage of any
architecture specific implementation details,

00:37:58.110 --> 00:37:59.130
especially extensions.

00:37:59.130 --> 00:38:02.200
Those'll have to be looked at.

00:38:02.200 --> 00:38:06.770
But the vast majority of the open GL code
will run absolutely identically on both platforms.

00:38:06.770 --> 00:38:08.740
&gt;&gt;Ian: You will need to be aware of one thing
though.

00:38:08.740 --> 00:38:09.740
&gt;&gt;Dan G: Yes.

00:38:09.740 --> 00:38:15.180
&gt;&gt;Ian: Which is because Android is an open
system, there's a huge number of OEMs.

00:38:15.180 --> 00:38:21.859
You can't make as many assumptions about the
GPU hardware as you can with some other systems.

00:38:21.859 --> 00:38:22.859
&gt;&gt;Dan g: Absolutely.

00:38:22.859 --> 00:38:27.500
&gt;&gt;Ian: So even though the open GLES ABI is
standard, some of the extensions that you

00:38:27.500 --> 00:38:33.040
may have come to rely on or possibly some
of the behaviors or even bugs that you may

00:38:33.040 --> 00:38:37.900
rely on one system are not necessarily going
to be the same on other systems.

00:38:37.900 --> 00:38:43.280
A good example of that is that PVR GPUs do
geometry sorting.

00:38:43.280 --> 00:38:49.500
So they're almost completely insensitive to
the way you submit geometry.

00:38:49.500 --> 00:38:52.320
But they are very sensitive to how many state
transitions you do.

00:38:52.320 --> 00:38:53.320
&gt;&gt;Dan G: yes.

00:38:53.320 --> 00:38:55.480
&gt;&gt;Ian: Where as Tegra GTUs are almost the
opposite.

00:38:55.480 --> 00:38:59.710
They change state very fast but you want to
always sort front to back.

00:38:59.710 --> 00:39:04.540
&gt;&gt;Dan G: exactly and so the real key, and
that's certainly, it's only one issue.

00:39:04.540 --> 00:39:07.910
There's also things like if you wanna use
texture compression.

00:39:07.910 --> 00:39:09.650
You know, there is not a standard.

00:39:09.650 --> 00:39:10.650
&gt;&gt;Ian: Everybody's got their own thing.

