&gt;&gt;Dan G: High performance ones used on Android,
there's also you know, there are also issues

00:39:17.070 --> 00:39:20.910
in terms of how you should write your shaders.

00:39:20.910 --> 00:39:24.750
And you know, making sure that you're really
querying very carefully.

00:39:24.750 --> 00:39:29.490
Also making sure that you do test those shaders
on a variety of GPUs. 'cause you will see

00:39:29.490 --> 00:39:32.160
different performance cliffs from device to
device.

00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:37.000
That being said, from a coding perspective,
your code is going to, what you really have

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:40.450
to look at is audio 'cause the audio standards
are very very different.

00:39:40.450 --> 00:39:44.390
You're gonna look at touch and events which
are very very different.

00:39:44.390 --> 00:39:47.900
Networking actually if you're not using SSL,
you can just use sockets.

00:39:47.900 --> 00:39:51.430
And so your socket code will come over pretty
much straight, to be honest.

00:39:51.430 --> 00:39:54.740
So there's a lot you do get a lot.

00:39:54.740 --> 00:39:58.080
You can actually use even threading you can.

00:39:58.080 --> 00:39:59.450
If you're using standard p-threads.

00:39:59.450 --> 00:40:04.520
If you, as long as you're not relying on making
calls back into the Dalvik virtual machine

00:40:04.520 --> 00:40:06.550
you can actually use those very easily.

00:40:06.550 --> 00:40:10.760
Or you can actually tie those back into Dalvik
threads.

00:40:10.760 --> 00:40:15.869
And there's actually a really nice library
that Invidia has provided for doing that.

00:40:15.869 --> 00:40:20.380
So there really are a lot of things you can
do and really one of the main reasons we do

00:40:20.380 --> 00:40:28.730
the NDK is to allow people to take advantage
of tested code sections that you, code libraries.

00:40:28.730 --> 00:40:31.370
That you have a written for another platform.

00:40:31.370 --> 00:40:35.270
So from that perspective, that plus the standard
APIs do provide a really nice basis.

00:40:35.270 --> 00:40:36.270
Especially for games.

00:40:36.270 --> 00:40:40.800
Where it gets more challenging is when you
want to take advantage of the Android standard

00:40:40.800 --> 00:40:42.560
UI patterns.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:44.430
And those are, there's a lot of useful stuff
in there.

00:40:44.430 --> 00:40:46.900
